var tafsirData_14 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Ra": "These are letters from the Arabic alphabet that appear at the beginning of some chapters of the Quran. Their full meaning is known only to Allah. They serve to capture the attention of the listener and demonstrate that the Quran, though composed of familiar letters, is a miraculous Book that no human can produce.",
    "˹This is˺ a Book which We have revealed to you ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah is addressing Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) directly, affirming that this Quran is not of human origin. It was sent down from Allah Himself as divine revelation. The Prophet did not author it; he received it through the angel Jibreel (Gabriel). This establishes the Quran's authority and authenticity as the Word of Allah.",
    "so that you may lead people out of darkness and into light": "The primary purpose of the Quran is transformation and salvation. 'Darkness' refers to ignorance, disbelief, false worship, injustice, and all forms of misguidance. 'Light' refers to faith, knowledge, truth, and the clarity that comes from following Allah's guidance. Just as a person lost in a dark forest needs a light to find their way, humanity needs the Quran to escape the darkness of confusion and sin. The Prophet's mission was to be a guide using this divine light.",
    "by the Will of their Lord": "Guidance only happens when Allah permits it. The Prophet can show the way and deliver the message, but ultimately, it is Allah who opens hearts and grants true guidance. This reminds us that we should always ask Allah for guidance and never become arrogant, thinking we guided ourselves. It also comforts the Prophet that not everyone will accept, and that is by Allah's decree.",
    "to the Path of the Almighty, the Praiseworthy": "The destination of this guidance is the path that leads to Allah—the One who is 'Al-Aziz' (the Almighty, possessing all power and honor) and 'Al-Hamid' (the Praiseworthy, deserving all praise for His perfection). This path is Islam, the way of submission to the One true God. Walking this path leads to Allah's pleasure in this life and Paradise in the next."
  },
  2: {
    "Allah, to Whom belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth": "This is a powerful declaration of Allah's absolute ownership and sovereignty. Everything that exists—the stars, planets, angels, humans, animals, plants, mountains, oceans—all belong to Him. He created them, sustains them, and controls them. Nothing escapes His dominion. When we understand this, we realize that we too belong to Allah, and we should live according to His guidance. A servant does not disobey the Master who owns everything.",
    "And woe to the disbelievers because of a severe torment": "'Woe' is an expression of intense warning and impending destruction. This is a serious caution to those who reject faith in Allah and His message. The 'severe torment' refers to the punishment in the Hellfire. This warning is not meant to scare people away but to wake them up to the reality of their choices. Allah, out of His mercy, warns before He punishes, giving people time to repent and return to Him."
  },
  3: {
    "˹They are˺ the ones who favour the life of this world over the Hereafter": "These disbelievers prioritize temporary worldly pleasures—wealth, status, power, and enjoyment—over the eternal life to come. They live as if this world is all there is, ignoring the reality of death and what follows. This is like someone who spends all their money on a single night of entertainment while ignoring their entire future. The wise person invests in the Hereafter while still living responsibly in this world.",
    "and hinder ˹others˺ from the Way of Allah": "Not only do they reject guidance themselves, but they actively work to prevent others from accepting Islam. They might mock believers, spread lies about the religion, or persecute those who follow the truth. This is a grave sin because they are not just harming themselves but also blocking others from salvation. The leaders of Quraysh in Makkah did exactly this—they tried every method to stop people from listening to the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).",
    "striving to make it ˹appear˺ crooked": "They try to distort the truth, making the straight path of Allah seem confusing, unreasonable, or undesirable. They raise doubts, spread misconceptions, and twist the message to turn people away. For example, they might say that Islam is too strict, or that it doesn't fit modern life, when in reality, Islam is perfectly balanced and suitable for all times.",
    "It is they who have gone far astray": "Allah concludes by declaring their ultimate state: they are deeply lost. Their misguidance is not minor; it is severe and far-reaching. They have wandered so far from the truth that returning becomes increasingly difficult without sincere repentance. This is a warning to anyone who follows their path."
  },
  4: {
    "We have not sent a messenger except in the language of his people": "This demonstrates Allah's mercy and wisdom. Every messenger was sent speaking the native language of his community. Moses spoke the language of the Israelites, Jesus spoke Aramaic, and Muhammad (peace be upon them all) spoke Arabic. Why? So that the message would be clear and easily understood. Allah did not want language to be a barrier to understanding His guidance. This shows that Allah wants people to truly comprehend and benefit from His message, not just hear it.",
    "to clarify ˹the message˺ for them": "The purpose of sending messengers in their people's language was to make the message crystal clear. The messengers explained Allah's commands, warnings, and promises in a way their people could fully grasp. They removed any excuse for misunderstanding. This means that on the Day of Judgment, no one can say, 'I didn't understand the message.' Allah made it plain through His messengers.",
    "Then Allah leaves whoever He wills to stray and guides whoever He wills": "After the message is clearly delivered, the outcome depends on Allah's will. Those who sincerely seek truth with humble hearts are guided, while those who arrogantly reject despite understanding are left to their misguidance. This is divine justice—Allah does not force anyone, but He knows who deserves guidance based on their inner state and choices. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said: 'O turner of hearts, keep my heart firm upon Your religion' (Tirmidhi), showing that even the Prophet sought Allah's guidance constantly.",
    "And He is the Almighty, All-Wise": "Allah is 'Al-Aziz'—no one can override His decisions or escape His power. And He is 'Al-Hakeem'—every decision He makes is based on perfect wisdom, even if we don't immediately understand it. His guidance and His allowing some to stray are both rooted in wisdom and justice."
  },
  5: {
    "Indeed, We sent Moses with Our signs": "Allah sent Prophet Moses (Musa) equipped with clear miracles and proofs—such as his staff turning into a serpent, his hand glowing white, and the parting of the sea. These signs were evidence of his prophethood and the truth of his message. Just as Muhammad was given the Quran, Moses was given miracles suited to his time and people.",
    "˹ordering him,˺ 'Lead your people out of darkness and into light'": "Moses' mission was identical in essence to Muhammad's: to guide people from ignorance and disbelief (darkness) to faith and knowledge (light). The Children of Israel were enslaved in Egypt, oppressed by Pharaoh, and had lost much of their religious identity. Moses came to liberate them physically and spiritually.",
    "and remind them of Allah's days ˹of favour˺": "'Allah's days' refers to significant events in history when Allah showed His power—either by blessing and saving the believers or by destroying the disbelievers. Moses was to remind his people of how Allah saved previous nations, punished tyrants, and favored the righteous. Remembering these events strengthens faith and gratitude. We too should remember Allah's blessings upon us and the lessons from history.",
    "Surely in this are signs for whoever is steadfast, grateful": "The stories of the past contain powerful lessons, but only those with two qualities will truly benefit: 'Sabbar' (steadfast)—those who patiently endure hardships while holding onto faith, and 'Shakur' (grateful)—those who appreciate Allah's blessings and thank Him. Patience and gratitude together form the foundation of a strong believer. When tested, be patient; when blessed, be grateful."
  },
  6: {
    "˹Consider˺ when Moses said to his people, 'Remember Allah's favour upon you'": "Moses reminded his people to reflect on Allah's blessings. Gratitude begins with remembrance. When we forget what Allah has done for us, we become ungrateful and arrogant. Moses wanted his people to never forget their history and how Allah rescued them.",
    "when He rescued you from the people of Pharaoh": "The Children of Israel were slaves in Egypt under the brutal rule of Pharaoh and his regime. They had no power, no freedom, and no dignity. Allah, through Moses, delivered them from this oppression. This was a monumental favor that changed their entire existence.",
    "who afflicted you with dreadful torment—slaughtering your sons and keeping your women": "Pharaoh's cruelty was extreme. He ordered the killing of newborn boys among the Israelites because he feared a prophecy that a child from them would overthrow him. The women were kept alive to serve as slaves. Imagine the horror of mothers having their babies taken and killed. This was systematic genocide and oppression of the worst kind.",
    "That was a severe test from your Lord": "Even this suffering was a test from Allah. Tests come in many forms—sometimes through hardship, sometimes through ease. The test during Pharaoh's time was whether the Israelites would remain faithful and patient or lose hope and abandon their beliefs. Allah tests people to purify them, raise their ranks, and distinguish the sincere from the hypocrites."
  },
  7: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when your Lord proclaimed": "Allah made a clear announcement—a divine promise and warning. This wasn't a suggestion but a declared law from the Lord of the worlds. When Allah proclaims something, it is certain to happen.",
    "'If you are grateful, I will certainly give you more'": "This is one of the most hopeful verses in the Quran. Gratitude attracts more blessings. When you thank Allah for what you have—your health, family, food, faith—He increases it. Gratitude can be shown through the heart (feeling thankful), the tongue (saying Alhamdulillah), and actions (using blessings in ways that please Allah). The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) would pray at night until his feet swelled, and when asked why, he said, 'Should I not be a grateful servant?' (Bukhari). Gratitude is the key to abundance.",
    "'But if you are ungrateful, surely My punishment is severe'": "Ingratitude leads to loss of blessings and invites punishment. When people take Allah's favors for granted, deny His blessings, or use them in disobedience, they risk having those blessings taken away. History is full of nations that were blessed but became arrogant and ungrateful, and Allah destroyed them. This is a serious warning to reflect on our own gratitude."
  },
  8: {
    "Moses added, 'If you along with everyone on earth were to be ungrateful'": "Moses emphasized a profound truth: even if every single human being on the entire planet were to reject Allah and be ungrateful, it would not diminish Allah in any way. Our worship benefits us, not Him. Our ingratitude harms us, not Him.",
    "'then ˹know that˺ Allah is indeed Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy'": "Allah is 'Al-Ghani'—completely free of any need. He does not need our prayers, our thanks, or our worship. He is perfect and complete without any of His creation. And He is 'Al-Hamid'—worthy of all praise regardless of whether anyone praises Him. The angels, the heavens, the earth—all of creation glorifies Him. Our gratitude is for our own benefit, and our ingratitude only harms ourselves."
  },
  9: {
    "Have you not ˹already˺ received the stories of those who were before you": "Allah is addressing the people of Makkah, asking them to reflect on history. The stories of previous nations were known through oral traditions and should have served as warnings. The question format is meant to make them think deeply.",
    "the people of Noah, 'Âd, Thamûd, and those after them": "These are famous nations that rejected their prophets and were destroyed. Noah's people denied him for 950 years until the flood drowned them. 'Âd were a powerful people destroyed by a fierce wind. Thamûd rejected Prophet Salih and killed the miraculous she-camel, so an earthquake annihilated them. And there were many more nations after them.",
    "Only Allah knows how many they were": "The number of destroyed nations is so vast that only Allah has complete knowledge of them all. This emphasizes the magnitude of the warning—countless civilizations have come and gone because they rejected Allah's messengers.",
    "Their messengers came to them with clear proofs": "Every nation received a messenger with undeniable evidence—miracles, logical arguments, and divine revelation. The truth was made clear to them; they had no valid excuse to reject.",
    "but they put their hands over their mouths": "This is a gesture expressing either their attempt to silence the messengers, their shock and disbelief, or their arrogant rejection—as if trying to push back the message. It shows their refusal to even engage with the truth.",
    "and said, 'We totally reject what you have been sent with'": "They openly declared their disbelief. Despite seeing clear signs, they chose denial. This was not ignorance but willful rejection.",
    "'and we are certainly in alarming doubt about what you are inviting us to'": "They claimed to have serious doubts about the message of monotheism and the Day of Judgment. But this doubt was not sincere seeking—it was an excuse to avoid change. True doubt leads to investigation, but their doubt was a cover for arrogance."
  },
  10: {
    "Their messengers asked ˹them˺, 'Is there any doubt about Allah, the Originator of the heavens and the earth?'": "The messengers responded with a powerful rhetorical question. How can anyone doubt the existence of Allah when the evidence is everywhere? Look at the sky, the earth, the sun, the moon, your own body—all of creation points to a Creator. Allah is 'Fatir'—the One who originated and created everything from nothing. Doubt about Allah is irrational when signs of His existence surround us.",
    "He is inviting you in order to forgive your sins": "The purpose of Allah's message is not to burden people but to save them. Allah is offering forgiveness for past sins to anyone who believes and repents. This is an invitation of mercy, not condemnation. How generous is a Lord who calls sinners to be forgiven!",
    "and delay your end until your appointed term": "By accepting faith, they would be spared immediate punishment and allowed to live until their natural death. Rejecting faith might bring destruction sooner—as happened to many nations. Allah was giving them more time to live and benefit from His guidance.",
    "They argued, 'You are no more than humans like us!'": "This was a common objection throughout history. People expected messengers to be angels or supernatural beings. They couldn't accept that a regular human—eating, sleeping, walking among them—could receive divine revelation. But this objection misses the point: Allah chose humans to be messengers precisely so they could relate to their people and serve as practical examples.",
    "'You ˹only˺ wish to turn us away from what our forefathers worshipped'": "They accused the messengers of trying to destroy their traditions. Following ancestors blindly was their excuse for rejecting truth. But truth doesn't depend on tradition. If ancestors were wrong, following them leads to destruction. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) faced the same argument from the Quraysh, who insisted on following their forefathers' idol worship.",
    "'So bring us some compelling proof'": "They demanded miracles or supernatural evidence. Yet, even when miracles were shown, many still rejected. Their demand was often not sincere—they were looking for excuses, not truth."
  },
  11: {
    "Their messengers said to them, 'We are ˹indeed˺ only humans like you'": "The messengers humbly acknowledged their humanity. They didn't claim divinity or supernatural status. Their greatness came not from being non-human but from being chosen by Allah. This humility is a lesson for all leaders and teachers—power and authority come from Allah, not from our own qualities.",
    "'but Allah favours whoever He chooses of His servants'": "Prophethood is a divine selection. Allah knows who is most suitable to carry His message. He chose Ibrahim, Musa, Isa, Muhammad (peace be upon them all) based on His perfect wisdom. No one can claim prophethood; it is purely Allah's gift.",
    "'It is not for us to bring you any proof without Allah's permission'": "Miracles are not magic tricks performed on demand. They come only when Allah wills. The messengers could not produce signs whenever asked—only when Allah authorized them. This teaches us that all power belongs to Allah; even prophets are dependent on Him.",
    "'And in Allah let the believers put their trust'": "The verse concludes with a call to Tawakkul—complete trust and reliance on Allah. Believers should not be shaken by rejection or demands for proof. They trust Allah's plan, knowing He will support them."
  },
  12: {
    "'Why should we not put our trust in Allah, when He has truly guided us to ˹the very best of˺ ways?'": "The messengers expressed their complete confidence. Allah had already guided them to the truth—the best path possible. Having received such a favor, how could they not trust Him completely? This is a lesson: once you have found Allah's guidance, trust Him fully in all matters.",
    "'Indeed, we will patiently endure whatever harm you may cause us'": "The messengers declared their commitment to patience despite persecution. They knew the path of truth comes with trials. This is the attitude of true believers—they don't abandon their faith when tested. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) and his companions faced torture, boycotts, and exile, yet they remained steadfast.",
    "'And in Allah let the faithful put their trust'": "This phrase is repeated for emphasis. Trust in Allah is the foundation of faith. Those who truly believe place their affairs in Allah's hands, knowing He is the best disposer of all matters."
  },
  13: {
    "The disbelievers then threatened their messengers, 'We will certainly expel you from our land'": "When arguments failed, the disbelievers resorted to threats and force. This is a pattern throughout history—those in power often use exile and persecution against those who speak the truth. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) himself was forced to leave Makkah and migrate to Madinah.",
    "'unless you return to our faith'": "They gave an ultimatum: abandon your message and follow our religion, or leave. This shows they understood the message was a threat to their power and status quo. True faith cannot be abandoned for worldly safety, and the messengers refused.",
    "So their Lord revealed to them, 'We will surely destroy the wrongdoers'": "Allah responded to the threats against His messengers with a promise of divine intervention. The 'wrongdoers' (Zalimeen) would face destruction. This is Allah's justice—He defends His messengers and punishes those who oppose the truth."
  },
  14: {
    "'and make you reside in the land after them'": "Allah promised the believers that they would inherit the land from which the disbelievers tried to expel them. Those who threatened exile would themselves be removed, and the believers would take their place. This happened with the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him)—he was expelled from Makkah but returned victorious, and Islam spread throughout Arabia.",
    "'This is for whoever is in awe of standing before Me and fears My warning'": "This promise is for those who have Khashya—a deep awareness and fear of standing before Allah on the Day of Judgment. They take Allah's warnings seriously and live accordingly. Such people will be given victory and establishment in the earth."
  },
  15: {
    "And both sides called for judgment": "Both the believers and disbelievers sought Allah's judgment—each confident they were right. The messengers prayed for victory and vindication, while the disbelievers arrogantly challenged Allah to send punishment if the message was true.",
    "so every stubborn tyrant was doomed": "The result was clear: every 'Jabbar' (arrogant tyrant) and 'Anid' (stubborn rejecter) was defeated and ruined. History testifies to this—Pharaoh drowned, the people of 'Âd were swept away, Thamûd were destroyed. Arrogance against Allah always leads to failure."
  },
  16: {
    "Awaiting them is Hell": "After their worldly destruction, an even worse fate awaits in the Hereafter. Hell is their final destination—a place of unimaginable torment prepared for those who rejected Allah.",
    "and they will be left to drink oozing pus": "The description is graphic and horrifying. Instead of water, they will be given 'Sadeed'—the pus and bodily fluids that ooze from the wounds of the people of Hell. This is the 'drink' of the damned, a stark contrast to the pure rivers of Paradise. Such descriptions are meant to make us reflect on the reality of punishment and motivate us to seek Allah's mercy."
  },
  17: {
    "which they will sip with difficulty, and can hardly swallow": "The drink is so repulsive that they will struggle to get it down. Each sip is torture. Unlike the cool, refreshing drinks of Paradise, this drink increases their suffering.",
    "Death will overwhelm them from every side, yet they will not ˹be able to˺ die": "The suffering will be so intense that they will wish for death, but death will not come. Normally, extreme pain leads to death as a release, but in Hell, there is no escape. They will experience pain from every direction—physical, mental, emotional—yet remain conscious to feel it all.",
    "Awaiting them still is harsher torment": "And this is not even the worst of it. Beyond what is described, there is even more severe punishment. The horror compounds, emphasizing the need to avoid such a fate through faith and good deeds."
  },
  18: {
    "The parable of the deeds of those who disbelieve in their Lord is that of ashes": "Allah uses a vivid image to explain the reality of disbelievers' actions. Imagine ashes—the remnants of something burned, already worthless and without substance.",
    "fiercely blown away by wind on a stormy day": "Now imagine those ashes caught in a violent storm. They scatter everywhere, impossible to gather. This is what happens to the good deeds of disbelievers—their charity, their help to others, their worldly achievements—all become worthless because they lacked the foundation of faith. Without belief in Allah, even good actions have no lasting value in the Hereafter.",
    "They will gain nothing from what they have earned": "On the Day of Judgment, they will find nothing in their account. All their worldly accomplishments—wealth accumulated, buildings constructed, fame achieved—will not benefit them at all. The currency of the Hereafter is faith and righteous deeds done for Allah's sake.",
    "That is ˹truly˺ the farthest one can stray": "This is the ultimate misguidance—to work hard in life yet end up with nothing because the foundation was wrong. Imagine building a beautiful house on sand; when the flood comes, it all collapses. This is why faith is essential; it gives meaning and permanence to our actions."
  },
  19: {
    "Have you not seen that Allah created the heavens and the earth for a reason?": "Allah did not create the universe randomly or as a joke. Everything was created with purpose, wisdom, and truth. The stars, the planets, the ecosystems—all function according to Allah's design. Similarly, human life has purpose: to worship Allah and be tested. This understanding gives meaning to our existence.",
    "If He wills, He can eliminate you and produce a new creation": "Allah is not dependent on humanity. If He wished, He could remove all of us and bring entirely new beings into existence. This is a humbling reminder that we are not essential to Allah's plan. He keeps us because of His mercy, not His need. It also serves as a warning: do not think your rejection of faith harms Allah—He can replace you instantly."
  },
  20: {
    "And that is not difficult for Allah ˹at all˺": "Replacing humanity or creating new worlds is effortless for Allah. He only says 'Be' and it is. What might seem impossible to us is simple for the Creator of all existence. This reinforces the earlier point—we should never feel that our worship is a favor to Allah. It is purely for our own benefit."
  },
  21: {
    "They will all appear before Allah": "On the Day of Judgment, every soul—leaders and followers, rich and poor, powerful and weak—will stand before Allah. No one can hide or escape. All worldly distinctions will vanish.",
    "and the lowly ˹followers˺ will appeal to the arrogant ˹leaders˺, 'We were your ˹dedicated˺ followers'": "Those who blindly followed misguided leaders—whether religious, political, or social—will turn to them for help. They will say: we followed you, we obeyed you, we did what you told us. Now save us!",
    "'so will you ˹then˺ protect us from Allah's torment in any way?'": "The followers will desperately ask their leaders for help. But on that Day, no one can help anyone else escape Allah's punishment. The bonds of this world—loyalty, friendship, allegiance—will mean nothing.",
    "They will reply, 'Had Allah guided us, we would have guided you'": "The leaders will make excuses, blaming Allah for their misguidance. But this is a lie—Allah sent messengers and clear signs. They rejected guidance by choice. Now they try to deflect responsibility.",
    "'˹Now˺ it is all the same for us whether we suffer patiently or impatiently, there is no escape for us'": "The leaders admit defeat. Whether they scream and complain or try to be patient, the punishment is certain. There is no way out. This scene should make us reflect: who are we following? Will those we follow be able to help us on that Day?"
  },
  22: {
    "And Satan will say ˹to his followers˺ after the judgment has been passed": "After the final judgment is made and destinies are sealed, Satan—the ultimate deceiver—will address all those who followed him.",
    "'Indeed, Allah has made you a true promise'": "Satan will acknowledge that everything Allah promised—the Day of Judgment, Paradise, Hell, rewards, and punishments—was true. Allah's word was always honest and reliable.",
    "'I too made you a promise, but I failed you'": "Satan admits he lied. He promised pleasure, success, and that there would be no consequences for sin. All of it was deception. He never intended to fulfill any promise; he only wanted to lead people astray.",
    "'I did not have any authority over you'": "This is crucial: Satan had no real power over anyone. He couldn't force anyone to sin. He had no army, no weapons, no control. All he did was suggest and whisper.",
    "'I only called you, and you responded to me'": "Satan simply invited people to disobey Allah, and they accepted willingly. Every sin committed was a personal choice. This destroys the excuse of 'Satan made me do it.' He only called; humans answered.",
    "'So do not blame me; blame yourselves'": "Satan refuses to take responsibility. He tells his followers to blame themselves for choosing to listen to him instead of Allah. The blame falls entirely on those who had the ability to choose right but chose wrong.",
    "'I cannot save you, nor can you save me'": "On the Day of Judgment, Satan will be just as helpless as his followers. He cannot rescue anyone, and no one can rescue him. Every soul will face its own fate.",
    "'Indeed, I denounce your previous association of me with Allah ˹in loyalty˺'": "Satan disowns his followers completely. Whatever loyalty they showed him in the world, he rejects it now. He denies any partnership or bond with them. Those who obeyed Satan instead of Allah will find themselves utterly abandoned.",
    "'Surely the wrongdoers will suffer a painful punishment'": "The scene ends with a declaration of the inevitable: those who did wrong—following Satan, rejecting Allah—will face severe, painful punishment. This verse is a profound warning to reflect on whose voice we listen to in life."
  },
  23: {
    "Those who believe and do good": "After describing the horrors awaiting disbelievers, Allah now presents the beautiful contrast—the reward for those who combined faith with righteous action. Belief alone is not enough; it must be accompanied by good deeds. Similarly, deeds without proper faith lack foundation.",
    "will be admitted into Gardens, under which rivers flow": "Paradise is described with rivers flowing beneath lush gardens. These rivers are not just water—there are rivers of milk, honey, and pure wine in Paradise (as mentioned in Surah Muhammad). The imagery represents abundance, beauty, and peace beyond imagination.",
    "to stay there forever by the Will of their Lord": "Unlike worldly pleasures that end, Paradise is eternal. There is no fear of death, no anxiety about losing blessings. And this eternal stay is by Allah's permission and grace—even Paradise is a gift from Him, not something earned purely by deeds. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said: 'No one will enter Paradise by their deeds alone.' When asked, 'Not even you?' He replied, 'Not even me, unless Allah covers me with His mercy' (Bukhari).",
    "where they will be greeted with 'Peace!'": "The greeting in Paradise is 'Salaam'—peace. This is the ultimate state: peace from all worries, fears, pain, and negativity. Angels will greet the believers with peace, and Allah Himself will greet them with peace, as mentioned in other verses. What greater honor could there be?"
  },
  24: {
    "Do you not see how Allah compares a good word to a good tree?": "Allah uses the parable of a tree to illustrate the nature of good speech—the word of faith (La ilaha illallah), words of truth, beneficial knowledge, and sincere advice. Just as a tree is valuable and beautiful, so is good speech.",
    "Its root is firm": "A good tree has deep, strong roots that anchor it firmly in the ground. Similarly, the word of faith and truthful speech are rooted in certainty, knowledge, and sincerity. They cannot be easily uprooted or shaken by doubts and challenges. A believer's faith, when true, remains firm through trials.",
    "and its branches reach the sky": "The tree grows upward toward the heavens. Good words and true faith ascend to Allah. They reach high and have far-reaching effects. A single word of truth can influence generations. The testimony of faith elevates a person's soul to the highest levels."
  },
  25: {
    "˹always˺ yielding its fruit in every season by the Will of its Lord": "A good tree continuously produces fruit—not just once, but consistently throughout the year. Similarly, good words and true faith produce continuous benefits. A believer's good deeds, prayers, charity, and kindness keep yielding rewards. Even after death, ongoing charity (Sadaqah Jariyah), beneficial knowledge, and righteous children continue to benefit the believer.",
    "This is how Allah sets forth parables for the people": "Allah uses comparisons and examples to make complex concepts easy to understand. Parables help people visualize abstract truths. The Quran is full of such teaching methods because Allah wants us to truly comprehend, not just hear.",
    "so perhaps they will be mindful": "The purpose of these parables is to awaken people's hearts and minds, to make them reflect and remember. Those who ponder these examples will be guided, while those who ignore them remain heedless."
  },
  26: {
    "And the parable of an evil word is that of an evil tree": "In contrast, evil speech—words of disbelief, lies, slander, and harmful talk—is compared to a bad tree. Some scholars identify this as the colocynth plant (Hanzal), which is bitter and useless.",
    "uprooted from the earth": "Unlike the good tree with firm roots, this evil tree has been torn out of the ground. It has no foundation, no stability. Evil words and false beliefs may seem attractive temporarily, but they have no lasting basis.",
    "having no stability": "The evil tree cannot stand, cannot grow, and cannot produce lasting fruit. Similarly, falsehood cannot endure. Lies are eventually exposed, disbelief leads to destruction, and evil speech brings no lasting benefit. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said: 'Truth leads to righteousness, and righteousness leads to Paradise... Falsehood leads to wickedness, and wickedness leads to the Fire' (Bukhari). This parable urges us to be mindful of our words and to build our lives on the solid foundation of faith and truth."
  },
  27: {
    "Allah makes the believers steadfast with the firm Word ˹of faith˺": "Allah grants stability and firmness to those who believe through the 'firm word'—which scholars explain as the testimony of faith (La ilaha illallah - There is no god but Allah). This declaration is the foundation of a believer's life. It keeps them grounded during trials, temptations, and doubts. When life shakes us, this firm word keeps us anchored. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) explained that this firmness will be especially important in the grave when the angels question the deceased about their Lord, religion, and Prophet. Those with true faith will answer correctly, while others will fail.",
    "in this worldly life and the Hereafter": "This steadfastness is not limited to this world. In this life, believers are kept firm against misguidance, peer pressure, and the whispers of Satan. In the Hereafter—specifically in the grave and on the Day of Judgment—they will remain firm when questioned and tested. Faith provides stability in every phase of existence.",
    "And Allah leaves the wrongdoers to stray": "In contrast, those who commit injustice and persist in sin are left without this divine support. Their hearts become hardened, their vision becomes clouded, and they drift further from the truth. This is not arbitrary—it is a consequence of their own choices. They rejected guidance, so Allah withdrew His assistance.",
    "For Allah does what He wills": "Allah's decisions are based on perfect wisdom and justice. He guides whom He wills and leaves astray whom He wills—but always in accordance with what people deserve based on their intentions and actions. No one can question His authority, and no one can escape His decree."
  },
  28: {
    "Have you not seen those ˹disbelievers˺ who meet Allah's favours with ingratitude": "Allah draws attention to a particular type of wrongdoer—those who receive countless blessings from Allah but respond with denial and disbelief. Instead of thanking Allah for health, wealth, family, and guidance, they reject Him and attribute their success to themselves or false gods. This refers specifically to the leaders of Quraysh who received the honor of being custodians of the Kaaba and living in the sacred city of Makkah, yet they rejected the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) and fought against Islam.",
    "and lead their own people to their doom": "These ungrateful leaders don't just harm themselves—they drag their followers down with them. By rejecting truth and spreading falsehood, they cause their entire community to fall into destruction. This is the heavy responsibility of leadership: a misguided leader can destroy an entire nation. The 'doom' here refers to both worldly ruin (like the defeat at Badr) and eternal punishment in the Hereafter."
  },
  29: {
    "In Hell they will burn": "The ultimate destination of these ungrateful disbelievers is Hellfire. They will enter it and experience its intense burning—a physical and spiritual torment beyond imagination. The Arabic word 'yaslawnaha' implies they will be thoroughly exposed to its heat.",
    "What an evil place for settlement": "Hell is described as the worst possible abode. Unlike a home that provides comfort and security, Hell offers only suffering, regret, and despair. This is the 'settlement' they chose by rejecting Allah's blessings and guidance."
  },
  30: {
    "They set up equals to Allah to mislead ˹others˺ from His Way": "These disbelievers committed the grave sin of shirk—associating partners with Allah. They worshipped idols, ancestors, or other beings alongside Allah. Worse still, they actively worked to mislead others, promoting their false beliefs and turning people away from the true path of Islam. Setting up 'equals' to Allah is the greatest injustice because it denies the Creator His right to exclusive worship.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ 'Enjoy yourselves!'": "The Prophet is commanded to deliver a stern message to these people. The phrase 'enjoy yourselves' is not an encouragement—it is a warning dripping with irony. Go ahead and enjoy your temporary pleasures, your wealth, your status—but know that it will all end soon.",
    "'Surely your destination is the Fire'": "No matter how much they enjoy this world, their final destination is the Hellfire. This brief enjoyment will be followed by eternal suffering. This warning should make anyone who hears it reconsider their choices. The pleasures of this world are fleeting; the Hereafter is forever."
  },
  31: {
    "Tell My believing servants": "Allah instructs the Prophet to convey a message specifically to the believers. The use of 'My servants' shows Allah's special relationship with those who believe—they belong to Him and He cares for them. This address carries honor and responsibility.",
    "to establish prayer": "Prayer (Salah) is the first command—the pillar of Islam after the testimony of faith. 'Establishing' prayer means more than just performing it; it means praying consistently, on time, with proper focus (khushu'), and fulfilling all its conditions. Prayer is the direct connection between the servant and Allah, and it distinguishes believers from disbelievers.",
    "and donate from what We have provided for them": "The second command is spending in Allah's cause from the wealth He has given. Notice that Allah says 'what We have provided'—a reminder that all wealth ultimately comes from Him. This includes obligatory charity (Zakat), voluntary charity (Sadaqah), and spending on family and those in need.",
    "openly and secretly": "Charity should be given in both ways. Sometimes giving publicly encourages others to give and is appropriate for communal projects. Other times, giving secretly is better because it protects the giver from showing off and preserves the dignity of the receiver. The best charity is often that which the left hand doesn't know what the right hand gives.",
    "before the arrival of a Day in which there will be no ransom or friendly connections": "This creates urgency. The Day of Judgment is coming—a Day when no amount of money can buy salvation and no friendships or family connections will help. On that Day, everyone stands alone before Allah. So spend now, pray now, do good now—before it's too late. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said: 'The feet of a servant will not move on the Day of Judgment until he is asked about his life, his knowledge, his wealth, and his body' (Tirmidhi)."
  },
  32: {
    "It is Allah Who created the heavens and the earth": "Allah begins by reminding us of the greatest act of creation—the heavens with their stars and galaxies, and the earth with its mountains, oceans, and ecosystems. All of this was created by Allah alone, without partner or helper. This is the foundation of all other blessings.",
    "and sends down rain from the sky": "Rain is a fundamental blessing that sustains all life. Allah controls the water cycle—evaporation, cloud formation, and precipitation—with perfect precision. Without rain, there would be no drinking water, no agriculture, and no life. Every drop of rain is a sign of Allah's mercy.",
    "causing fruits to grow as a provision for you": "From the rain, Allah causes plants to grow and fruits to develop. The variety of fruits—apples, oranges, grapes, dates, mangoes—each with unique taste, color, and nutrition, demonstrates Allah's creativity and generosity. All of this is 'rizq' (provision) from Allah for human benefit.",
    "He has subjected the ships for your service, sailing through the sea by His command": "Allah made the oceans navigable and gave humans the knowledge to build ships. Throughout history, ships have been essential for trade, travel, and exploration. The fact that massive vessels can float and travel across vast oceans is by Allah's design and permission.",
    "and has subjected the rivers for you": "Rivers provide fresh water, irrigation for crops, transportation, and sustenance for communities. Allah created rivers flowing through lands, making civilization possible. The Nile, the Tigris, the Euphrates—all are blessings from Allah."
  },
  33: {
    "He has ˹also˺ subjected for you the sun and the moon, both constantly orbiting": "The sun provides light, warmth, and energy essential for life on Earth. The moon provides light at night and affects the tides. Both celestial bodies follow precise orbits without deviation—a testament to Allah's perfect design. They have been 'subjected' to serve humanity, not worshipped as gods as some ancient people believed.",
    "and has subjected the day and night for you": "The alternation of day and night is a profound blessing. Day provides light for work, activity, and productivity. Night provides darkness for rest, sleep, and recovery. This cycle regulates human life, agriculture, and the entire ecosystem. Imagine if it were always day or always night—life would be impossible."
  },
  34: {
    "And He has granted you all that you asked Him for": "Allah provides for His creation even before they ask, and He responds to prayers and needs. Everything humans possess—health, family, intelligence, opportunities—comes from Allah. Even the needs we didn't know to ask for, He provided.",
    "If you tried to count Allah's blessings, you would never be able to number them": "This is a profound statement. Try to count Allah's blessings: every breath, every heartbeat, every moment of sight, every sip of water, every night of sleep, every loving relationship, every skill you have. You would never finish counting. Scholars say even the blessing of being able to count is a blessing! This should inspire overwhelming gratitude.",
    "Indeed humankind is truly unfair, ˹totally˺ ungrateful": "Despite receiving countless blessings, humans often fail to appreciate them. We are 'zaloom' (unjust to ourselves by sinning) and 'kaffar' (ungrateful, denying Allah's favors). We complain about what we lack instead of thanking Allah for what we have. We use His blessings to disobey Him. This verse is a wake-up call to examine our own gratitude."
  },
  35: {
    "˹Remember˺ when Abraham prayed, 'My Lord! Make this city ˹of Mecca˺ secure'": "Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham), peace be upon him, made heartfelt supplications to Allah. His first request was for the safety and security of Makkah—the city where he had left his wife Hajar and son Ismail near the Kaaba. Security is a fundamental blessing; without it, worship, trade, and daily life become impossible. Allah answered this prayer—Makkah became a sanctuary where even in pre-Islamic Arabia, enemies would not fight each other within its boundaries.",
    "and keep me and my children away from the worship of idols": "Ibrahim's second prayer shows his deep concern for spiritual safety. He had witnessed idol worship destroy nations and understood its danger. He prayed for himself and his descendants to be protected from this sin. This teaches us that righteous people worry about their faith and their family's faith. We should also pray for ourselves and our children to be kept firm on Tawheed (monotheism)."
  },
  36: {
    "'My Lord! They have caused many people to go astray'": "Ibrahim explains why he fears idols so much—they have misled countless people throughout history. Nations have worshipped statues of stone and wood, sacrificed for them, and even killed for them. The attraction to idol worship has been a recurring human weakness, and Ibrahim sought Allah's protection from it.",
    "'So whoever follows me is with me'": "Ibrahim identifies true followers—not by lineage or tribe, but by belief and practice. Those who follow his path of pure monotheism and submission to Allah are his true family. This principle is important: in Islam, faith matters more than blood relation.",
    "'and whoever disobeys me—then surely You are ˹still˺ All-Forgiving, Most Merciful'": "Even for those who disobey, Ibrahim does not call for their destruction. Instead, he leaves their matter to Allah, reminding us of Allah's mercy and forgiveness. This shows Ibrahim's compassionate nature and his trust in Allah's ultimate justice and mercy. It's a lesson in not giving up on people and always hoping for their guidance."
  },
  37: {
    "'Our Lord! I have settled some of my offspring in a barren valley, near Your Sacred House'": "Ibrahim recalls his act of faith—leaving his wife Hajar and infant son Ismail in the empty, barren desert valley of Makkah, near the site where the Kaaba would be built. There was no water, no vegetation, no people—only rocks and sand. This was an incredible test of trust in Allah, and Ibrahim passed it.",
    "'our Lord, so that they may establish prayer'": "The purpose of this settlement was spiritual, not worldly. Ibrahim left them there so that they could establish prayer and worship near the Sacred House. This shows that the primary purpose of our lives should be worship of Allah. Ibrahim prioritized his family's spiritual mission over their material comfort.",
    "'So make the hearts of ˹believing˺ people incline towards them'": "Ibrahim prayed that people would be drawn to this place and to his family. Allah answered magnificently—Makkah became the spiritual center of the world, with millions of Muslims longing to visit, performing Hajj and Umrah. Hearts from every nation 'fly' towards Makkah with love and devotion.",
    "'and provide them with fruits, so perhaps they will be thankful'": "In a barren desert, Ibrahim asked Allah for provision—fruits and sustenance. Today, Makkah receives fruits and goods from all over the world. What was once an empty valley is now a thriving city with every provision available. And the purpose of this provision? So that the people would be grateful to Allah."
  },
  38: {
    "'Our Lord! You certainly know what we conceal and what we reveal'": "Ibrahim acknowledges Allah's complete knowledge. Allah knows every secret thought, hidden intention, and private action, as well as everything done openly. This is comforting for the sincere believer—Allah knows your true intentions even if others misunderstand you. And it's a warning for hypocrites—nothing is hidden from Allah.",
    "'Nothing on earth or in heaven is hidden from Allah'": "Ibrahim emphasizes this truth with absolute clarity. Whether in the depths of the ocean, the darkness of night, the privacy of your home, or the vastness of space—nothing escapes Allah's knowledge. He knows the falling leaf, the ant beneath the rock, and the thought before it forms. This awareness should inspire mindfulness (Taqwa) in everything we do."
  },
  39: {
    "'All praise is for Allah who has blessed me with Ishmael and Isaac in my old age'": "Ibrahim expresses deep gratitude for one of his greatest blessings—his children. For most of his life, Ibrahim was childless, which was a source of great longing. Then, in his old age, Allah blessed him with Ismail (from Hajar) and later Ishaq/Isaac (from Sarah). Both became prophets, and from them came great nations. This is a reminder that Allah's blessings may come late, but they are always worth waiting for.",
    "'My Lord is indeed the Hearer of ˹all˺ prayers'": "Ibrahim testifies that Allah hears and answers prayers. Despite waiting decades for children, his prayers were answered. This should give hope to everyone making dua—Allah hears every supplication, even the silent whispers of the heart. The answer may come immediately, be delayed, or come in a different form, but Allah always responds in the best way."
  },
  40: {
    "'My Lord! Make me and those ˹believers˺ of my descendants keep up prayer'": "Ibrahim's concern for prayer continues. He asks Allah to make him consistent in establishing prayer—not just praying, but truly establishing it with regularity, devotion, and excellence. And he extends this prayer to his descendants, wanting his family to be a lineage of worshippers. This teaches parents to prioritize their children's spiritual development and to make dua for their guidance.",
    "'Our Lord! Accept my prayers'": "Ibrahim humbly asks Allah to accept his supplications. Even a great prophet does not assume his prayers are automatically accepted—he asks with humility. This teaches us that acceptance of deeds is not guaranteed; we should always ask Allah to accept our worship and good deeds."
  },
  41: {
    "'Our Lord! Forgive me, my parents, and the believers'": "Ibrahim asks for forgiveness for himself, his parents, and all believers. This comprehensive prayer shows his concern for the entire Muslim Ummah across time. Note: Regarding his parents, this prayer was made before Ibrahim knew his father would die as a disbeliever. Once it became clear his father rejected faith, Ibrahim disassociated from him in this matter, as mentioned elsewhere in the Quran. We are also encouraged to pray for forgiveness for believing parents and all Muslims.",
    "'on the Day when the judgment will come to pass'": "Ibrahim specifies the Day of Judgment—the Day when accounts are settled and destinies determined. Forgiveness on that Day is the ultimate success, for it means being saved from Hell and admitted to Paradise. This is the day everyone should prepare for."
  },
  42: {
    "Do not think ˹O Prophet˺ that Allah is unaware of what the wrongdoers do": "This verse addresses a question that may arise: why do oppressors and evildoers seem to prosper without punishment? Allah reassures the Prophet and all believers that He sees everything. Not a single act of injustice—whether a tyrant oppressing millions or a person wronging their neighbor—escapes Allah's knowledge. Allah is never unaware, never sleeping, never distracted.",
    "He only delays them until a Day when ˹their˺ eyes will stare in horror": "The delay in punishment is not neglect—it is a postponement to a specific Day. On the Day of Judgment, their eyes will be frozen open in shock and terror, unable to blink, staring at the horrors unfolding before them. The delay was actually worse for them, as it allowed their sins to accumulate while they felt falsely secure."
  },
  43: {
    "rushing forth, heads raised": "On that Day, the wrongdoers will rush forward in panic, their heads lifted upward—not in pride, but in fear, looking at the sky for what is descending upon them. They will be in a state of complete submission and helplessness.",
    "never blinking": "Their eyes will be fixed, unable to blink or look away from the terrifying scenes. In this world, we blink constantly without thinking; on that Day, even this automatic function will stop due to overwhelming horror.",
    "hearts void": "Their hearts will be empty—void of hope, courage, understanding, and peace. Fear will have evacuated everything from their hearts. They will be shells of people, present but completely hollow inside. This is the psychological state of the doomed on Judgment Day."
  },
  44: {
    "And warn the people of the Day when the punishment will overtake ˹the wicked among˺ them": "The Prophet is commanded to warn people about the Day of Judgment. This is the core of prophetic mission—delivering the warning clearly so that people have no excuse. The punishment will 'overtake' them suddenly, giving no chance to escape.",
    "and the wrongdoers will cry, 'Our Lord! Delay us for a little while'": "When punishment becomes real, the wrongdoers will beg for more time. 'Just a little longer!' they will plead. This is the same request people make when death approaches—wishing for more time to do good. But it will be too late.",
    "'We will respond to Your call and follow the messengers!'": "They will make promises they never intended to keep in this world. 'If only we had more time, we would believe and follow the prophets!' But these are empty words. In this life, they had decades to respond and refused.",
    "'˹It will be said,˺ \"Did you not swear before that you would never be removed ˹to the next life˺?\"'": "They will be confronted with their own previous denial. They used to swear there was no afterlife, no resurrection, no judgment. Now faced with reality, their denial is thrown back at them. This is a reminder that our words and beliefs will be held against us if we reject the truth."
  },
  45: {
    "'You passed by the ruins of those ˹destroyed peoples˺ who had wronged themselves'": "Allah reminds them of the evidence they had. The Arabs used to travel through the ruins of destroyed nations like Thamud (in northern Arabia) and the people of Lot (near the Dead Sea). They saw the remnants of civilizations destroyed for their disbelief. These were not just tourist sites—they were warnings.",
    "'It was made clear to you how We dealt with them'": "The stories of these destroyed peoples were well-known. The Quran also recounts them in detail. There was no excuse for ignorance—Allah made the lessons clear through ruins, through oral traditions, and through revelation.",
    "'and We gave you ˹many˺ examples'": "Allah provided numerous examples and parables to guide people. Every destroyed nation was a case study in what happens when people reject truth. Yet, despite all these examples, many still refused to take heed."
  },
  46: {
    "They devised every plot": "The disbelievers throughout history have schemed against Allah's messengers and the believers. They have used deception, propaganda, violence, and every tactic imaginable to suppress the truth. The leaders of Quraysh plotted to kill the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) on the night of his migration to Madinah.",
    "which was fully known to Allah": "Every secret meeting, every whispered conspiracy, every hidden plan was completely known to Allah. Nothing happens without His knowledge. The plotters think they are clever, but Allah is the best of planners.",
    "but their plotting was not enough to ˹even˺ overpower mountains ˹let alone Allah˺": "This powerful phrase shows the futility of their schemes. Even if their plots were so massive they could move mountains, they would still be nothing against Allah's power. Some scholars interpret this as: their plots were indeed mountain-sized in their own view, but they could never challenge Allah's decree. Others interpret it as: their plots could never succeed in removing Islam, which is as firm as mountains."
  },
  47: {
    "So do not think ˹O Prophet˺ that Allah will fail to keep His promise to His messengers": "Allah reassures the Prophet and all believers: every promise Allah made to His messengers—of victory, support, and the defeat of disbelievers—will be fulfilled. Allah never breaks His word. The messengers may face temporary hardship, but ultimate success belongs to them.",
    "Allah is indeed Almighty, capable of punishment": "Allah is 'Aziz'—possessing all might and power—and 'Dhun-tiqam'—capable of taking retribution against those who deserve it. This combination of attributes assures the believers that justice will be served. The oppressors will face consequences, and the believers will be vindicated."
  },
  48: {
    "˹Watch for˺ the Day ˹when˺ the earth will be changed into a different earth and the heavens as well": "On the Day of Judgment, this entire universe will be transformed. The earth we know will be replaced with another earth—white, flat, and radically different. The heavens too will be changed. This transformation marks the end of the world as we know it and the beginning of eternal existence. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was asked about where people will be when this happens, and he said they will be on the Sirat (bridge over Hell) or similar positions of reckoning.",
    "and all will appear before Allah—the One, the Supreme": "Every single creation—humans, jinn, animals—will stand before Allah. He is 'Al-Wahid' (the One, unique in His divinity) and 'Al-Qahhar' (the Supreme, the Irresistible). On that Day, no one will have any power, any argument, or any escape. All will be completely subject to Allah's authority."
  },
  49: {
    "On that Day you will see the wicked bound together in chains": "The criminals—those who committed grave sins and rejected faith—will be chained together. Perhaps partners in crime will be chained to each other, or all criminals of similar types grouped together. This is humiliation and restraint, the opposite of the freedom and power they enjoyed while sinning in this world."
  },
  50: {
    "with garments of tar": "Instead of fine clothes, the wicked will be dressed in garments of 'qatiran'—tar or pitch. Tar is black, sticky, flammable, and intensely hot. It will cling to their bodies, increasing their torment and burning their skin. This is the 'clothing' of the people of Hell.",
    "and their faces covered with flames": "Fire will engulf their faces—the most honorable and sensitive part of the body. They once used their faces to express arrogance, mockery, and denial. Now, those same faces will burn. The Quran often mentions faces being in Fire as a sign of ultimate disgrace."
  },
  51: {
    "As such, Allah will reward every soul for what it has committed": "This is the principle of divine justice. Every soul—good or evil—will receive exactly what it earned. Good deeds will be rewarded with Paradise; evil deeds will be punished with Hell. No one will be wronged, no good deed will be lost, and no sin will be overlooked unless Allah forgives it through His mercy.",
    "Surely Allah is swift in reckoning": "Despite the billions of humans and jinn being judged, Allah's reckoning is swift. He does not need time to calculate or consider—His knowledge is perfect and immediate. The entire judgment process, though comprehensive, will happen with divine efficiency. Some scholars say this also means the Day of Judgment is near in the divine perspective."
  },
  52: {
    "This ˹Quran˺ is a ˹sufficient˺ message for humanity": "The Quran is Allah's final communication to all of humanity—not just Arabs, not just the Prophet's contemporaries, but every person until the Day of Judgment. It is 'balagh'—a complete, clear, and sufficient message. Nothing essential for guidance has been left out.",
    "so that they may take it as a warning": "The primary purpose of this message is to warn people. Warn them of what? Of the Day of Judgment, of Hell, of the consequences of disbelief and sin, of the plots of Satan, and of the temporary nature of this world. A person who takes heed of these warnings will change their life accordingly.",
    "and know that there is only One God": "The core message of the Quran is Tawheed—the absolute oneness of Allah. There is no god worthy of worship except Allah alone. No partners, no intermediaries, no rivals. Understanding this truth is the foundation of salvation. Without it, nothing else matters.",
    "and so that people of reason may be mindful": "'Ulul-Albab'—people of intellect, understanding, and insight—are specifically addressed. True intelligence leads to recognizing the truth of the Quran. Those with sound minds who sincerely reflect will find guidance. Being mindful means remembering Allah, thinking about the Hereafter, and living consciously according to divine guidance. The Surah ends with a call to reflection, urging every thinking person to take this message seriously."
  }
};